multi-region conjugate heat transfer
====================================

Two solvers: chtMultiRegionSimpleFoam (steady) and
chtMultiRegionFoam (transient). The agent picks between them based
on the time scheme.

Use for heat transfer between solids and single-phase fluids — air,
water, oil, cryogens (LN2, LH2, LOX). Anywhere the energy equation
needs to cross from a fluid into a solid and back out into another
fluid. Not for boiling, condensation, or phase change.


what makes CHT different
------------------------

  - Multiple regions in one mesh. The mesh carries cellZones
    (gmsh Physical Volumes) that splitMeshRegions turns into
    separate per-region polyMesh trees.

  - Coupled interfaces. _to_ patches connect two regions.
    OpenFOAM solves the energy equation on each region
    independently and uses compressible::turbulentTemperatureCoupledBaffleMixed
    on the interface so T and heat flux match.

  - The case has tree shape. Files live at 0/<region>/<field>,
    system/<region>/, constant/<region>/. The top-level
    system/ only holds controlDict, fvSchemes, and
    fvSolution.

  - Per-region thermophysical properties. Each fluid region has
    its own thermophysicalProperties — water on one side, LN2 on
    the other, air in a third. Solids carry heSolidThermo with
    their own ρ, Cp, κ.


how the agent renders a CHT case
--------------------------------

The CHT solver plugins are mostly deterministic. The LLM only
generates system/controlDict. Everything else
(constant/regionProperties, per-region thermo, per-region
fvSchemes/fvSolution, per-region 0/* fields including coupled
interface BCs) is built in Python by MultiRegionBase
(simd_agent/solvers/families/_multi_region.py).

Why? CHT case files are highly structured and the LLM gets details
wrong (kappaMethod direction, coupling BC name, mapping
patch type). A deterministic renderer driven by typed RegionSpecs
is faster, more reliable, and easier to keep correct across
OpenFOAM versions.

The LLM contributes one file. The orchestrator validates everything
through plugin.validate_full(). Per-patch values still come from
the user's wizard / precheck via the enrichment pipeline.


region detection
----------------

simd_agent/run/multi_region/region_detection.py auto-detects CHT
topology from the mesh:

  1. cellZones (preferred) — gmsh Physical Volume names are
     authoritative. A region exists iff its cellZone exists in the
     mesh, independent of patch naming.

  2. patch-prefix fallback — when cellZones are missing, the
     detector groups mesh patches by the substring before the first
     underscore (innerFluid_inlet, innerFluid_outlet →
     innerFluid).

Each detected region gets classified as fluid or solid via name
heuristics (wall, solid, metal, steel, tube, pipe,
shell → solid; everything else → fluid). The
RegionExtractor LLM then refines presets and fills inlet values
from the user's prompt.


per-region fluid presets
------------------------

MultiRegionBase.FLUID_REGION_PRESETS ships ready-to-use property
sets for: air, water, oil, ln2, lox, lh2, lng, lhe,
helium. Each carries Cp, mu, Pr, rho_nominal, and the
thermo_profile (gas vs cryogenic).

The enrichment step region_fluid_presets
(simd_agent/run/enrichment/region_fluid_presets.py) infers each
region's preset from:

  1. the case's fluid name (e.g. "Liquid Nitrogen (LN2)" → ln2),
  2. the region's T_init (77 K → ln2, 290 K → water),
  3. the case's bulk density,
  4. regasifier topology rule: when exactly one cryogenic
     region exists alongside a room-temperature region defaulting
     to air, the room-T region flips to water — air at 1.2 kg/m³
     carries ~1000× less enthalpy than the LN2 side, which makes
     the heat-exchange visualization useless.

Any preset already set to a non-default value (by the
RegionExtractor LLM or the UI) is preserved.


per-region BCs
--------------

simd_agent/solvers/families/_multi_region_bcs.py builds each
field file. Each builder:

  - walks the region's patches (those matching <region>_*),
  - picks a role-appropriate BC body (inlet, outlet, wall,
    symmetry, empty),
  - emits the coupled-baffle block on every _to_ interface.

Builders exist for: T, U, p, p_rgh, k, epsilon,
omega, nut, alphat.

The turbulence-field set is single-sourced via
MultiRegionBase.turbulence_fields(model) — which appends alphat
(the compressible companion of nut) to whatever the single-region
default returns. Without alphat the solver aborts at startup
with "cannot find file 0/<fluid>/alphat".


mesh patch types after splitMeshRegions
---------------------------------------

After splitMeshRegions, the sim-server runs a per-region
fix_boundary_types pass that:

  - coerces patches with wall-function BCs to type wall,
  - leaves mappedPatch interfaces alone (the coupled-baffle BC
    requires them).

The exclusion is critical. Without it, the renderer would coerce
innerFluid_to_wall to wall and OpenFOAM would crash with
"Type should be a mappedPatch".

See simd-ai/simd-agent-simulation:app/runner.py:fix_boundary_types.


fvSchemes
---------

Both fluid and solid regions get their own system/<region>/fvSchemes.
Fluid regions include a mandatory wallDist { method meshWave; }
block — required by OF v2406 for any region with wall-function
turbulence. Solid regions only declare laplacian(alpha,h).


decompose / reconstruct
-----------------------

The sim-server calls decomposePar -allRegions and
reconstructPar -allRegions for multi-region cases (not the bare
forms, which only see the top-level polyMesh).


examples
--------

  - examples/inner-outer-pipe/ — two-fluid heat exchanger,
    chtMultiRegionSimpleFoam, separated inner and outer pipes.
  - examples/cylindrical-cht/ — concentric LN2 regasifier,
    chtMultiRegionSimpleFoam. The walk-through in
    Documentation/examples/cylindrical-cht covers the regasifier
    topology rule and what counter-flow heat transfer should look
    like.
